We must “simulate” the cash‐account from the beginning of the period. In our data only the “Cash deposit” initial record contributes to the “cash on hand” – the “bank deposit” and “fixed assets” are not “cash on hand” even though they are recorded at the very start. In our sample the “Initial20231231001” row with type “Cash deposit” shows an amount of 3,000,000. That is our starting balance.

Then we “walk” through every transaction that uses “Cash” as its payment (or “receive”) method. For example, an expense paid “Cash” subtracts from the cash on hand, whereas a sale cleared “Cash” adds to it. (Transactions paid by Bank Transfer or recorded as “Account Receivable” do not affect the cash balance immediately.) Also note that non‐cash adjusting entries – for example depreciation or “Interest Receivables” that are “Unpaid” – do not alter your cash balance.

By “processing” every row in the table – subtracting amounts for every expense that was paid by Cash and subtracting any cash‐out purchase, and adding every cash receipt from a sale in which the receive method was “Cash” – we find that after all the “Cash”–based transactions the ending cash comes to about 4,878,309.30.

Thus the answer is:

